1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. b3 {Once d5 is played always respond with b3 in 
order to eliminate Black's options!} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c5 7. e3 b6 8. Bb2 
Bb7 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2d3,Bf1d1,Bd2d4,Gb1c3,Gb1d2][%csl Gd3] Nice move: 1) control 
d3 because it might become a target after Black plays dxc4 later on 2) Make 
space for the f1-Rook to go to d1, which will be helping to play d4 later on. 
Notice that the d1-Rook and the Queen are located on the same file! 3) A 
flexible move because it gives the b1-Knight time to decide to move to c3 or d2} 
Nc6 10. Rd1 {[%cal Bd2d4] the rook is located on the same file as the opponent 
queen, and supports the d4-push as well} d4 11. exd4 cxd4 12. Ne5 {[%cal 
Gg2b7,Ge5c6][%csl Rc6]} Nxe5 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bg2 $14 {[%csl 
Gg2,Gb2,Rc6,Ra6,Rb5,Re5] White has the advantage of the Bishop pair, and Black 
has problems on the light squares in the Queenside.} *

