1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. b3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. d4 {Always play 
d4 after O-O in order to avoid any annoying checks. Why are we choosing a 
Catalan set-up here? Because the White Bishop is located on c1. Let me show you 
why that makes a difference.} b6 8. Qc2 {Preparing for Rd1 followed by Nc3 and 
e4!} Nbd7 9. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8][%csl Rd8]} Bb7 10. Nc3 {[%cal Be2e4][%csl 
Rb7,Gc3] as long as the Bishop is not on a6 the Knight can go to c3, preparing 
for e4!} Rc8 11. e4 {[%csl Ge4] the key move in the Catalan is achieved!} dxe4 
12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 $16 {[%cal Ge4b7,Bc4c5][%csl Rb7,Rc6,Gc5] Again a typical 
position has been achieved, the main goal for White is to stop the c5-push!} *

