1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 {*General Plan:* In the Slav Black tries to consolidate the 
center and keep everything under control. White has to keep as much tension in 
the center as possible and can try to attack on the Queenside. *Ideas:* • b3 
is an important move to avoid dxc4 variations. • Rc1-Rc2!? creates space for 
Qa1, Rfc1, Bc3, b4, b5 to fight on the Queenside. • If Black doesn't improve 
the light-squared Bishop and instead plays ...e6, we will gain a Catalan-like 
structure.} c6 3. b3 $5 {[%cal Gb3c4][%csl Gc4] A nice move to avoid ...dxc4.} 
(3. g3 {is one of the main lines, but we want to avoid dxc4.} dxc4) Bf5 (3... 
Nf6 4. Bb2 Bg4 (4... Bf5 5. g3 {Will be a transposition to the Bf5-line.}) 5. e3 
Nbd7 6. Be2 e6 7. h3 {kick the Bishop away! We will consider this position in 
more detail in the larger course.}) 4. Bb2 e6 {We are playing against the 
reversed London!} ({Black's main alternative here is} 4... Bg4 {, which the 
larger course spends 5 variations on. Our general idea is to chase that bishop 
and grab the bishop pair!}) 5. g3 {[%cal Bf1g2,Be1g1]} (5. d4 $6 {White 
shouldn't give up the control of the e4-square by pushing the d4-pawn to the 4th 
rank!}) Nf6 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O h6 {[%cal Gf5h7][%csl Gh7] In order to create 
space for the f5-Bishop on the h7-square!} 8. d3 {[%cal Bb1d2,Ba1c1] Note: If 
you have seen my other course on Chessable 1. b3 Fight Like Naka, then you can 
choose this variation.} Be7 (8... c5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. d4 {and Black will be 
suffering because of the isolated d-pawn!}) 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Rc1 (10. a3 $5 
{White wants to push b4, grabbing space on the Queenside and hoping for b5 later 
on.} a5 {To prevent the expansion on the Queenside!} 11. Ra2 $5 {Is another way 
of playing this position, the point is to make space for the Queen on a1! 
Followed by Bc3 and b4!}) Bh7 11. Rc2 $5 {[%cal Bd1a1] A very nice idea is 
placing the Queen on the a1-square in order to create huge pressure on the a1-g7 
diagonal!} a5 {[%cal Ba5a4] Threatening ...a4 and causing some problems for 
White along the a-file.} 12. a3 {[%cal Ba5a4,Bb3b4] In order to meet ...a4 by 
pushing the pawn to b4.} Ne8 {[%cal Be7f6] One of the ideas for Black is to 
exchange the dark-squared Bishops which seems it will give Black an easier 
game!} 13. cxd5 exd5 (13... cxd5 14. Qa1 {Followed by Rfc1 and White will have 
better control over the c-file!}) 14. Qa1 {[%cal Ga1g7][%csl Rg7]} Bf6 {[%cal 
Bf6b2]} 15. Re1 {[%cal Be2e4] Preparing for the e4 break in the center!} Bxb2 
16. Qxb2 $14 {[%cal Bb3b4,Be2e4,Bb4b5][%csl Rb7,Rc6] White has two main ideas 
here. A minority attack, which is done by playing b4-b5, or going for the center 
by pushing the e-pawn forward!} *

