1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O ({This move is interchangeable 
with} 5. Nc3 {.}) e5 6. Nc3 Nge7 {*General Plan:* Black is closing the center by 
choosing this structure, aiming for good control over the d4-square and a main 
focus on the Kingside. White will be working on the Queenside. *Ideas:* • 
Black will start expanding on the Kingside, moving the f-pawn forward after 
finishing the development. White has to manage to play the b4-push as quick as 
possible, sometimes costing a pawn sacrifice to be on time.} 7. a3 {White is 
preparing to attack the c5-pawn using the b4-push.} O-O 8. b4 $1 {[%cal 
Bb4c5][%csl Rc5] This is my recommendation against the ...c5-d6-e5 setup. In the 
main course I spend 23 variations looking at this aggressive move.} cxb4 (8... 
d6 9. Rb1 {and the c8-Bishop cannot move because b7 will be unprotected!} f5 10. 
Ne1 Rb8 11. Nc2 Be6 12. Ne3 {and White is on time to prevent d5 and to control 
the d5-square.}) 9. axb4 Nxb4 {Accepting the pawn is a dangerous idea.} 10. Ba3 
{[%cal Ga3f8][%csl Rf8,Re7,Rb4]} Nec6 11. Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5b4,Ga3b4][%csl Rb4]} 
Nxd5 (11... e4 {Attacking the Knight and the Rook at the same time!} 12. Nxb4 
exf3 13. Bxf3 {Regaining the pawn.} Nxb4 14. Bxb4 Bxa1 15. Qxa1 $1 {White wants 
to make use of the very weak dark squares.} Re8 16. Qd4 {Threatening Bc3, and 
preventing the d-pawn from moving!} f6 17. Bc3 d6 18. h4 h5 19. Rb1 $16 {and 
Black is paralyzed!}) 12. Bxf8 Qxf8 13. cxd5 $16 {And White is up material!} *

